data.enText: to say officially that sth has a particular character or name; to describe sth in a particular way

data.hoverText: 动词+名词短语+名词短语

data.enText: This area has been designated (as) a National Park.
This floor has been designated a no-smoking area.

data.chText: 几名学生被认定有一定或严重学习困难。
data.enText: Several pupils were designated as having moderate or severe learning difficulties.

data.chText: 选定，指派，委任（某人任某职）
data.enText: to choose or name sb for a particular job or position

data.chText: 主任获准选定自己的继任人。
data.enText: The director is allowed to designate his/her successor.

data.chText: 她委任了谁为她的副手？

data.hoverText: 动词+名词短语+名词短语

data.enText: Who has she designated (as) her deputy?

data.chText: 被指派接替校长职务的男人

data.hoverText: 动词+名词短语+带to的不定式

data.enText: the man designated to succeed the president
to show sth using a particular mark or sign

data.chText: 不同的类型分别用字母A、B和C标明。
data.enText: The different types are designated by the letters A, B and C.

data.chText: （已受委派）尚未上任的；（已当选）尚未就职的
data.enText: chosen to do a job but not yet having officially started it
an interview with the director designate

simple_means.memory_skill: de 使… + sign 信号 + ate 使… → 发出信号 → 指示

means: 选定，指派，委任(某人任某职)

ex.chText: 她被任命为约克市邮政局局长。
ex.enText: She was appointed (as) postmaster of the city of York.

ex.chText: 我们委派他为委员会成员。
ex.enText: We appointed him to the committee.

synonyms.bx: 指不经投票选举等而直接指派。常可与介词 as 连用，但现在经常将其省略。

ex.chText: 他选定了谁当他的副手？
ex.enText: Who has he designated (as) his deputy?

ex.chText: 她被选派接任财务主管的职务。
ex.enText: She was designated to take over the position of treasurer.

synonyms.bx: 通常指为某项工作或某个目的而任命，多用被动语态。

ex.enText: The president named her (as) Secretary of the State.

ex.chText: 她30岁的时候被主席选入该委员会。
ex.enText: At the age of 30, she was named to the committee by the chairman.

synonyms.bx: 指由官方选定某人或某物，尤指使其担任重要职务，常可与介词 as 连用，但现在经常将其省略。

ex.chText: 下月史密斯先生退休，布朗先生将获任命接替他的职位。
ex.enText: Next month Mr. Smith will retire and Mr. Brown will be nominated as his replacement.

ex.chText: 她被任命为委员会委员。
ex.enText: She was nominated to the committee.

synonyms.bx: 既可指提出人选，由有决策权的人定夺，也可指直接委任，常后接介词 as/to。

example: She was intended to become the director
She was destined to become a great pianist

tr: indicate a place, direction, person, or thing
example: I showed the customer the glove section
He pointed to the empty parking space

tr: assign a name or title to
give an assignment to (a person) to a post, or assign a task to (a person)

value.boxr_value: The verb is pronounced /'dezɪgneɪt/. The adjective is pronounced /'dezɪgnət/. 动词读作 /'dezɪgneɪt/，形容词读作 /'dezɪgnət/。

value.def: When you designate someone or something as a particular thing, you formally give them that description or name.

example.ex: ...a man interviewed in one of our studies whom we shall designate as E...
example.tran: 在我们的一项研究中接受访谈的男子，我们称之为 E

example.ex: There are efforts under way to designate the bridge a historic landmark...
example.tran: 人们正在努力将这座桥定为历史遗迹。

example.ex: I live in Exmoor, which is designated as a national park.
example.tran: 我住在埃克斯穆尔，那里已被命名为国家公园。

value.def: If something is designated for a particular purpose, it is set aside for that purpose.

example.ex: Some of the rooms were designated as offices.
example.tran: 其中一些房间被指定用作办公室。
专门给予少数族裔学生的奖学金

example.ex: Smoking is allowed in designated areas.
example.tran: 允许在指定区域内吸烟。

value.def: When you designate someone as something, you formally choose them to do that particular job.

example.ex: The President's designated successor is his son.
example.tran: 总统的选定继承人是他的儿子。

value.def: Designate is used to describe someone who has been formally chosen to do a particular job, but has not yet started doing it.

example.ex: Japan's Prime Minister-designate is completing his Cabinet today.
example.tran: 日本的当选首相今日将完成组阁。

value.tran: （已受委派）尚未上任的;（已当选）尚未就职的
